. The British Trials Collection contains the only readily accessible and near-verbatim accounts of civil trials from the 1760s, 1770s, and 1780s, decades crucial to understanding how the rules of evidence developed. It might be thought that Defence of the Realm Acts (DORA) or its regulations would have introduced trials in camera. The book presents a comparative critique of war crimes trials before the International Military Tribunals at Nuremberg and Tokyo and the International Tribunals for the former Yugoslavia and for Rwanda. The first spy trial by court martial after the legal change in 1915 was that of Robert Rosenthal, who was German. The book also considers the principal features of the first war crimes trial of the twenty-first century in terms of personnel and procedures, the alleged crimes, and issues of legality and legitimacy. It also speculates on the narratives or non-narratives of the trial and how these may impact on the professed aims and objectives of the litigation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAdministrative courtszEnglandxHistory. 0aAdministrative courtszEuropexHistory. 0aEcclesiastical courtszEnglandxHistory. 0aEcclesiastical courtszEuropexHistory. 0aTrialszEnglandxHistory. 0aTrialszEuropexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 18th Century.2bisacsh  aBritish Trials Collection.  aDefence of the Realm Acts.  aEnglish criminal courts.  aInternational Military Tribunals.  aInternational Tribunals for the former Yugoslavia.  aRobert Rosenthal.  aVictorian insanity trials.  aWestminster courts.  aalleged crimes.  acivil trials.  acourt martial.  acriminal lawyers.  ahomosexual offences.  alegality issues.  alegitimacy issues.